citations:
    citation-adwd-the-sacrifice:
        source: source-adwd
        properties:
            locator: "The Sacrifice"
            text_from_source: "Asha Greyjoy could taste the bile in the back of her throat. On the Iron Islands, she had seen priests of her own people slit the throats of thralls and give their bodies to the sea to honor the Drowned God. Brutal as that was, this was worse."
            accessed: "2026-03-06"
        notes: "Asha Greyjoy POV. Stannis Baratheon's host is snowbound at a crofter's village between two frozen lakes, three days' march from Winterfell for nineteen days. Four soldiers from Lord Peasebury's retinue are burned alive by the queen's men (Ser Godry Farring, Ser Clayton Suggs) as a sacrifice to R'hllor, having been caught eating a dead comrade. Stannis watches in silence then retreats to his watchtower. Arnolf Karstark has joined with 400 spears, a son Arthor, and three grandsons. The army is desperately short of food (down to 64 horses from 800) and fish from the frozen lakes is exhausted. Asha is a captive, guarded by Aly Mormont (the She-Bear). Ser Justin Massey advocates retreat; Ser Richard Horpe advocates pressing on. Tycho Nestoris of the Iron Bank of Braavos arrives by night with Tristifer Botley and other freed Iron Islanders, having ransomed them from Sybelle Glover. Nestoris brings two strangers found near Winterfell by Mors Umber — revealed to be Theon Greyjoy (emaciated, half his teeth gone, barely recognizable) and a young woman (Jeyne Poole, though not yet named in this chapter)."
